The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, April 30, 2004 				 Infocomm loss fails to slow down juggernaut
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Mumbai, April 29: Reliance Industries (RIL) has for the first time announced the performance of Reliance Infocomm, which has suffered a loss of Rs 265 crore in 2003-04, as part of its consolidated statement of accounts.																								RIL has invested over Rs 12,000 crore in Reliance Infocomm, which has made cash profits. According to vice-chairman and managing director Anil Ambani, no further capital contribution is expected from RIL. Reliance Infocomm will fund its future growth plans, he said.																								On a consolidated basis, RILs net profit rose to Rs 5,169 crore in 2003-04 from Rs 4,003 crore in the previous year. Reliance Energy contributed Rs 118 crore, IPCL Rs 63 crore and others (including Reliance Capital and Reliance Industrial Infrastructure) Rs 63 crore, Ambani added.																								If one were to deduct various provisions made and Reliance Infocomms loss of Rs 265 crore, the net profit of RIL on a consolidated basis would go up by over Rs 500 crore to Rs 5,674 crore, he said. Ambani also announced capital expenditure plans of Rs 35,000 crore spread over the next five years in oil exploration, retail and petrochemicals.																								Of this, about Rs 4,000 crore will be spent on exploration, Rs 15,000 crore on its gasfields in the Krishna-Godavari basin and transportation of gas, Rs 7,000 crore on its retail foray in petroleum products, Rs 6,000 crore in petrochemical capacities expansion and Rs 3,000 crore on modernisation and other capital expenditure.																								Ambani said the company will set up a new PTA capacity of over 5.32 lakh tonnes, fresh polyester filament yarn capacity of over 2.16 lakh tonnes, PSF of 2.16 lakh tonnes, polypropylene of 2.80 lakh tonnes, styrene of 5.50 lakh tonnes and butadiene of 6 lakh tonnes. 																								These expansions will be at RILs existing facilities at Hazira, Patalganga and Jamnagar. 
